.\" Manpage for kensa(1) — kensa CLI
.\" This file is the HAND-WRITTEN header. The body is generated
.\" from `bin/kensa <subcmd> --help` output by docs/man/gen-manpage.go.
.\" Run `make manpage` to regenerate dist/kensa.1; run
.\" `make manpage-check` to verify the committed copy is in sync.
.TH KENSA 1 "May 2026" "kensa v1.0" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
kensa \- atomic Linux configuration remediation with
capture/apply/validate/commit-or-rollback transactions
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B kensa
[\fI--db PATH\fR]
.I command
[\fIflags\fR] [\fIarguments\fR]
.PP
.B kensa
[\fI--help\fR | \fI--version\fR]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B kensa
is a compliance and atomicity engine for Linux configuration changes.
Every change runs as a four-phase transaction: capture the pre-state,
apply the change, validate the result, then commit or roll back. The
atomicity contract is the product; the compliance rules are the first
application of it.
.PP
The CLI surface is operator-facing: subcommands probe a host's
capabilities, run read-only compliance checks, apply remediations,
roll back past transactions, query the transaction log, and surface
session-aware drift reports. All transport defaults to system OpenSSH
(with ControlMaster connection sharing) so SSH agent, jump-host, and
known_hosts integration just works.
.PP
Rules are runtime input, not compiled in. The CLI requires
.I --rules-dir DIR
on most subcommands; the canonical 539-rule corpus ships separately
as the
.B kensa-rules
package.
.
.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help and exit. Use
.B kensa <command> --help
for subcommand-specific flags.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print the kensa binary version and exit.
.TP
.BR \-D " " \fIPATH\fR ", " \-\-db " " \fIPATH\fR
SQLite transaction-log path. Default: \fB.kensa/results.db\fR in the
current working directory. Required for
.B history
,
.B rollback
,
.B diff
, and
.B migrate
subcommands; optional elsewhere.
.
.SH COMMANDS
The following subcommands are documented in detail below. Each
section is generated from the live
.B kensa <command> --help
output so the manpage and the binary stay in sync.
.
